english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Equanimous Heart
  author: Lee Saeк
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A Buddhist monk from Caoxi came to see me by the Yellow Carp River and asked me to write an account of his Hall of Equanimous Heart, saying, "My teacher Huanan commanded this, and I hope you, sir, will expound upon its meaning."

    I am a Confucian scholar. The teachings of the Buddha that I have picked up along the way, I dare not speak aloud. So let me speak from what I have learned.

    When the heart dwells in heaven and earth, we call it the Luminous Mandate. This mandate is distributed equally to all things, yet among them, humans possess the greatest spiritual nature. Yet our vital essence is constrained by innate material endowment in front, and desire obscures us behind. From this arises the doctrine of the three grades of people. The sages worried about this, so they established teachings to clarify human relations and cultivated disciplined restraint to restore propriety. Thus the realm above and below, in all four directions, became balanced and perfectly ordered. This is what we Confucians say.

    That your teacher's teacher was skilled at discussing the meaning of the ancestors—this is what I have always admired. He analyzed the substance and function of the heart with great precision. What more could I add? When Bodhidharma, the twenty-eighth patriarch, first met Huike, in the moment of seeking the heart to settle the heart with the heart, the complete essence and marvelous function were revealed in full measure. It was transmitted to the Sixth Patriarch until the dharma spread throughout the ten directions. What more could I add? As for the Buddha plucking the flower on Vulture Peak and transmitting the ineffable mind of nirvana to Mahakasyapa—from the Western lands to the Eastern realm, through the generations the record has never ceased, and there have been many great masters. What more could I add?

    You are no ordinary being. You have transcended the common rank with none to stand as your equal. Thus you have received the title of one ascending the dharma stages. In observing the dharma, there is no high or low. In entering the way, there is no self and other. Therefore your heart is as clear as an ancient well, as broad as the great earth, or moving like a divine dragon raining upon all under heaven. How can such a heart be spoken of lightly?

    We Confucians cultivate the heart with equilibrium and govern the vital forces with ease, thereby perfecting ourselves and our households to bring peace to the world. But your aspiration goes further still. You embody all virtues and perfect all practices to become a guide for the three realms—is this so distant? No, it is not distant. Thus it is said: the three realms are nothing but mind; all dharmas are nothing but consciousness. How then could one debate whether it is balanced or not?

    Think on this, venerable one. Alas, I am old. My rambling words end here. Will you accept what I have said, or will you not? No matter—sit in equanimity upon your meditation seat.
  footnotes:
    - Caoxi refers to the lineage of Hui-neng, the Sixth Patriarch of Chan Buddhism in China, whose temple was located at Caoxi.
    - The 'three grades' refers to classifications of human nature based on innate capacity and moral development, concepts debated in Confucian and Neo-Confucian thought.
    - 'Bodhidharma and Huike: Huike (神光) was the second patriarch who sought out Bodhidharma to receive transmission of the dharma.'
    - The flower-plucking at Vulture Peak is a foundational Chan story where the Buddha silently transmits enlightenment mind to Mahakasyapa through a gesture.
    - Lee Saeк here bridges Confucian and Buddhist thought, showing how both traditions ultimately point to the cultivation of the peaceful heart.
